on contradictions of religious and national belonging as well as intersections of religion and nation in many different regions of the world from the 18th century until today. While illustrating the diversity and contradictions of religious and national belonging across time and space, the chapters of the book contribute to an understanding of the dynamics of questions of belonging and the associated constant renegotiations of power within these discursive processes.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aMarginalität. 4aMinderheit. 4aNation. 4aReligion. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Communication Studies.2bisacsh  aMarginality.  aMinority.  aNation.  aReligion.1 aAcke, Hanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAcke, Hanna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBock, Katharina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonacchi, Silvia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonacchi, Silvia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCzimbalmos, Mercédesz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEgry, Gábor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHadar, Maya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHitzke, Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJahns, Esther, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJunker, Carsten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLindberg, Svante, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNgouo, Herbert Rostand,